> Fun culinary and language fact: "Rosa" means "pink" in Italian. For our chefs' version of rigatoni rosa, you'll make a homemade rosa sauce with tomato paste, cream cheese, broth, and chili flakes (for a little heat!). Toss that with rigatoni, zucchini, and crumbled pork sausage, then sprinkle Parmesan all over and we promise: you'll be blushing from all the compliments you receive on this meal.

Wash and dry produce.

Bring a #large pot{} of salted water to a boil. Once water is boiling, add @rigatoni pasta{6%ounce}; cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings), then drain and set aside.

Meanwhile, trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; slice crosswise into 1/4-inch-thick half-moons. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

While pasta cooks, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add zucchini; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and tender, ~{5-6%minutes}. Remove pan from heat; transfer zucchini to a #plate{}.

Remove sausage from casing; discard casing.

Heat another drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @Italian pork sausage{9%ounce}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until almost cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes} (it'll finish cooking in the next step).

Stir garlic and @tomato paste{1.5%ounce} into pan with sausage; cook until garlic is fragrant, tomato paste is well distributed, and sausage is fully cooked, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @PHILADELPHIA® cream cheese{4%tablespoon}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, 1/2 cup reserved pasta cooking water (ladle straight from the pot if pasta hasn't finished cooking yet), @butter{1%tablespoon}, @sugar{1/2%teaspoon}, and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste. (For 4 servings, use ¾ cup pasta cooking water, 2 TBSP butter, and 1 tsp sugar.) Remove from heat.

Add drained rigatoni and zucchini to pan with sauce. Stir in half the @parmesan cheese{1/2%cup}. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

> TIP: If needed, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time until pasta is coated in a creamy sauce.

Divide between #bowls{}; top with remaining Parmesan and serve.